I recently took my car into this location for servicing. I paid to get an oil change, a tire rotation, and my check engine light checked. I dropped it off on Friday the 10th, and was able to get in contact with one of the service reps on Monday. The rep explained to me that the esim needed to be serviced and this was the reason for my check engine light. I picked my car up on Tuesday afternoon, where no one really briefed me on what was done just processed the payment and sent me off. Little did I know the tire rotation was never done. Today as I am running a quick errand the PSI light comes on and my tire pressure was on 10 when it normally is at 35. So, my tire was on flat which is a more than dangerous way to drive in the the rain. When I called an asked if the tire rotation had been completed because my tires weren‚Äôt retaining air the representative said ‚Äúthat there were nails in my two front tires and it was noted on my service papers‚Äù. This should have been verbalized to me prior to me driving off of their lot. The fact that they even let me drive off of the lot without telling me this, just makes me feel as though there was no regard for my safety. < Review>
I stopped by Burtons on my way home from work to take a look at all there gems and such because my wife is really into her stone and jewelry making hobbies once she finds that lil window of opportunity from being a full time mother. I haven't been to Burtons since 1988 when the Dodgers last won the World Series!!! It was a great experience for me,I reminisced with Bob there about a teacher of mine I had in Jr. High at Walker. The class was called "Lost Wax" and it was Awesome! Walt Johnson was the teacher and he as well as the class will always be a cherished memory in my head. It was a flashback that left me feeling happy and joyful. Thanks for that Bob! I ended up buying a gem to surprise my wife with when I got home and she loved it! It is beautiful. Thanks also to the young gem expert Matt who works there as well, he is just a book of knowledge it seems when it comes to gems and stones. At such a young age is remarkable. I would most definitely recommend to all my friends and family Burton's gems and opals I can't wait to bring my wife and daughter in there soon enough see you then guys thanks again<//Review>

Late Yelp Post (1/23/2016):
One of my favorite go-to places for a quick bite to eat in the morning. I love their chorizo burrito, and ham&cheese croissant sandwiches! They make fresh orange juice but it's a bit pricey. My boyfriend and I always come here for a well done breakfast bagel and burrito. He gets the breakfast bagel and I get the chorizo (with egg and cheese) burrito. They are both delicious! I cannot get enough of their freshly squeezed orange juice machine, although I feel like the machine wastes more oranges than needed. Their hot chocolate is also exceptional!< /Text>

<Review>Fantastic overall experience!

I know there are already a lot of good reviews, but I will add one more. I assume that many of you, like me, appreciate a review with a little detail.

I did the two day (with camping) South Fork American River trip. This trip included lunch on both days. You will probably be very pleasantly surprised at the effort they put into the lunch. One day was a great lunch meat spread with onions, lettuce, tomatoes, pickles, and four or five breads. As an appetizer, which was swerved while the River guides sliced veggies and setup, they served chips, honey crisp apple slices, and orange slices. Day two was delicious taco salad. Both days included cold water and cookies too.

They cooked breakfast on day two also. Eggs, bacon, and both blueberry and chocolate chip pancakes. Of course, coffee and juice too.

On day one, they guides cooked dinner, which was a tasty chicken and pasta dish. Some adult beverages were also provided.

The rafting experience was excellent. The guides really make the trip better, and in my case, our guide Evan was wonderful. He worked really hard to make sure we enjoyed our trip. On day two, we ‚Äúsurfed‚Äù Chili Bar, which was thrilling. Evan had to work hard (three tries, and he had to jump in the River to move the boat) to get our boat in this unique current.

They are very safety conscious: a good briefing, flotation devices, and a helmet. Also, you will practice basic safety commands on the river.

The rafting itself was very exciting. Especially on day one, the rapids are fun without feeling overwhelming.  I voluntarily went for a swim at one point‚Äîyes the water is cold!

The final rapid on day 2, ‚ÄúTroublemaker,‚Äù was without a doubt the most intimidating, but with a good, well-trained guide (OARS has their guides complete weeks of training before they lead customers down the river), you will be safe.  If you are worried about falling out involuntarily, it of course could happen if Mother Nature decides she wants to rock the boat hard enough, but no one on my crew fell out.

One of the kids said it‚Äôs like an ride/water park, but on a real river instead of some amusement park. I like this analogy.

Day one was 4-5 hours, including lunch. Day two was 2-3 hours, including lunch. They did a good job with the schedule. Day two is more thrilling, but that‚Äôs fine because you learn and gain confidence after day one. Note: you can do a day trip for either day one or two‚Äîday two includes the Chili Bar and Troublemaker rapids, day 1 includes rapids like ‚ÄúSatan‚Äôs cesspool.‚Äù

For the camping, we paid a little extra for the platform tent. This setup was perfect‚Äîclean, roomy tent with two beds and a porch. If you like relaxing in the evening while camping, you will enjoy this setup. I did not need to bring any of my own camping gear. They also provide bathrooms and showers (you need your own toiletries and towels).  I guess this is really glampimg, given that someone cooked my meals!

At the end of each rafting day, they had ice cold sodas waiting. This seems like a silly thing to mention, but, after hours in the sun paddling, the soda was the prefect touch and highlights their focus on the customer experience.

I hope to do an OARS trip in the future.

I highly recommend if you are looking for an ‚Äúadventure‚Äù vacation. Our trip included kids, and I think this trip is kid-friendly (but they do need to be able to swim). if you are unsure, day one is less intimidating.

There are maybe 10 competitors‚ÄîOARS in my opinion is the best option (after seeing the other boats and facilities and lunch etc).  Everyone I spoke with, from scheduling to the campsite to the rafting, was personable and friendly.

Again, the guide Evan went above-and-beyond.  We learned a lot, talked during the calm water, and really enjoyed ourselves.

Final note: please remember the guides work in the service industry. Please tip them for their effort!< /Review>< Gmap_id>

<rate>1</rate>< review>
Worst customer service I have literally *EVER* had.
Avoid using Uhaul all together if possible!! I'd give 0 or negative stars if possible.

We were moving from SF to Nevada and needed to move 2 motorcycles (clearly mentioned several times). We had one trailer guaranteed at one close location and it was pulled from under us the week we were moving. Our "reservation" moved to Redwood City (5x FARTHER away) where we were guaranteed the original sized trailer and the DAY BEFORE OUR MOVING,it was changed again. They made an unauthorized change to a smaller trailer (unacceptable for Our needs). We then had to (calmly) fight with the rep to get us either the same size or bigger at a uhaul location within a reasonable distance. Several back and forth calls and conversations included the following info:
- She could get us a bigger trailer for 2x the price but with a very small discount
- "Nothing she could do to get a reduced price"
- She agreed that the guaranteed emails and situation was bad customer service
- We mentioned at least 10+ times throughout all of the conversations that it's for motorcycles and we need a ramp
- We we're finally able to get the originally guaranteed price (remember the "absolutely nothing I can do"?)

Ok, re-guaranteed the trailer at the far location, fine. Paid for it over the phone.

We get to the location and they make us buy a trailer light converter to connect to our Jeep AFTER:
- giving us a trailer without a ramp (because lifting 2, 500+ lb motorcycles up a 6"+ trailer lip is easy...?)
- never mentioning the converter is needed
- saying "Yea, we might have one laying around inside"
- one of the cashiers gave us a "spare cord" that we literally would have had to strip the wires to in order to connect it to the jeep
- completely leaving us to basically wander while the rep went to help someone new
- telling us there "might be an extra ramp by the dumpster"

We finally found a broken ramp that went to a totally different type of trailer. Eventually got on our way, and headed home. I immediately called uhaul to file a formal complaint. I found out that *NONE* of my issues had been filed under my account. I went through my whole experience and the lady I worked with was shocked (she was the only person I do not have an issue with in this whole ordeal). She filed it, sent the request for refunds, and then I just waited.

2 weeks went by and I called to check in on the progress. Nothing had been done yet. The guy I spoke with re-filed it and re-sent an email to the "case manager". I finally got a call (which went to my voicemail) saying the case manager didn't find anything.

I called him the next day and I found out he was the manager at this Redwood location (oh boy), but had to leave my name and a message, since no-one at the loxation picked up and I was sent to a call center. I called again sms someone sis she called him and he said there was "nothing mentioned in any of the calls about motorcycles" which is obnoxious. At this point he's either lazy and didn't actually listen, doesn't have access to all of the calls, or didn't want to admit how bad the service was in order to not refund any money.

I was told I would get a call back from him "later that day" and I haven't recieved anything. I called again today, was on hold for someone to pick up for 13 minutes before being sent to the call center yet again.

This is ridiculous and I have been dealing with resolving these issues for 1 month now, still no results. I am NEVER using Uhaul again because of the experiences with the Bay Area locations in general.<//review>

I walk outside for a minute, do nothing, walk back inside, verifies I've moved my car.  Sure.  She skips me in line and helps the gentleman behind me in line (also there for a trailer).

< user_id>
106098604160762535677</user_id>
<user_name>missmary< /user_name><time>1574431433504< /time>< Rating>
5</Rating>
< Review>
John Muir called these The Range of Light and spent most of his life in them. Stretching 400 miles North to South with 22 passes and only 3 of those being open/maintained in the Winter due to heavy snowfall. There is a 137 mile stretch with no crossing roads at all. The Pacific Crest Trail runs on them. I was raised in them on the Western side. To me they are everything a mountain range should be~Beautful, remote, many different landscapes, some which are very hard to access.<//Review>

<username>missmary</username>< Resp>

<Text>John Muir called these The Range of Light and spent most of his life in them. Stretching 400 miles North to South with 22 passes and only 3 of those being open/maintained in the Winter due to heavy snowfall. There is a 137 mile stretch with no crossing roads at all. The Pacific Crest Trail runs on them. I was raised in them on the Western side. To me they are everything a mountain range should be~Beautful, remote, many different landscapes, some which are very hard to access.<//Text><Pictures>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipM-EWxR6k_VmB2ZPRAgp6sTvfyfNEqwYKLsqq7u=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPn8OflZNYfcriu-Q1cf4VOcrNBHcDxQGBzGv30=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMdVaBrGwGGxcb519J-f_5160ylpDql6aPPgK_K=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNU8mPXjvy7qzudWXHqOsY9GJe7-qgR9AEZMrMm=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNS1FD4ZEC5rM5EHJ95SL_OF-6FDQAdsneFLIW0=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOCjDvG5yc8GzyG6lVZpsLz15Nve51W8toeuRog=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPXP3uCwZn12sj31eCDqdRWQ5sA6rWliEtGIp33=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipP2kUKgqckR0WDE35pI7aFGODEm5Vb8D54eRJJf=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOK0JmDzT4ly5DrTMN68zUpnQUVatdGAH8s2Wxn=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPLy4DRQq_kXTuXjrPYyzYBZD0kM7VX7Hx0rDyz=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPjbT4-etwEAa_RzbWXQnJLHuSIAYzwHyufXneX=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]</Pictures><rating>5</rating></record>

< Name>
Elbereth DJ</Name>
< Date>
1579824296990</Date>
<Rate>5<//Rate>< review>
How do review a mountain?!?! I mean it's beautiful, fun, dangerous and breathtaking. When traveling threw the mountains it's very important to drive prepared. Especially in the winter time. People have been killed in their cars when trying to sit threw a sudden snow storm. Always pack food and water, even if you're just driving threw. There are many places to stop along the way for supplies before you head into the mountains so do it. CAMPERS: Please contact local Rangers when choosing a camp ground. Some places are open to the public and some are not. ALWAYS GET A FIRE PERMIT BEFORE YOU CAMP. Otherwise you can get a ticket. Enjoy the amazing mountains but be wise.<//review>

<Rate>5<//Rate>< Review>
The only time in my life I've ever seen wild horses running free was when I was driving across the Sierra Nevadas.  It was stunning as I realized what it was.  Strength and beauty, as these wild and free creatures blazed across the horizon off to my right.  Freaky.  I loved it so much I had to put it in a song.  It was one of the coolest things I've ever seen, but hard to explain to where you could ever feel what I did when I actually saw it.  Unusual freedom.  Thank God.</Review>

<Rate>5< /Rate>< Review>
One of North America's major ranges can not possibly be described in a review. We are talking about 1/4 or so of the State of California! Thousands of communities from the foothills to the alpine tundra, and over to the desert steppe of the Great Basin and Mojave. Casinos and snow bunnies to hardscrabble mining, logging and agricultural towns. Ghost towns, and somewhere is John C Fremont's lost cannon. And Yosemite national park, among other national parks. Human history, genocide and disaster. And the sublime, including the highest peak in the lower 48, Devil's Postpile, Mammoth. From Susanville through Truckee to Bishop and Tehachepe, you can't scratch the surface of it.</Review>

<Response>None<//Response>< review>
I live in the Eastern Sierra Nevada.  In a tourist town called Bishop, CA.  There are numerous 14,000 peak mountains Mt Whitney is only 45 miles south of Bishop.  This is God's Country, with many lakes ,and streams and adventures waiting to happen. Take 395 out of  Los Angeles freeway system south approximate travel time 4 hours to Bishop, CA on highway 395.  Or come north 395 out of Carson City, Reno, Nevada. It doesnt matter how you get here, you won't ever regret it.  Everyone loves the Sierra Nevada.</review>
